Multiple sclerosis: it is not just the medication that matters, but the will of the patient to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease, and a person with this diagnosis needs the care of a number of experts: a neurologist, a physiotherapist, aphorism, a urologist, an ophthalmologist, a psychologist, a psychiatrist and many other specialists.
However, it is not just about therapeutic care, for example, women with multiple sclerosis also need consultations if they decide to have a child, the care of these sufferers also includes social counseling, recommendations on housing arrangements, etc.
Yet all this is not enough: the development of the disease can be fundamentally influenced by the patient himself.
The more he actively fights the disease, the longer he can work and he doesn't have to fundamentally change the style of his life.
Indeed, as doctors point out, the passivity of the sufferers leaves room for disease activity.
For example, it is proven that regular movement significantly delays the time when a sufferer needs a compensatory device, such as a stick.
It is important that patients and their surroundings do not succumb to different myths, such as that the disease automatically leads them to end up in a wheelchair.
That is why the Get a Chance page (www.bezmytu.cz) was created, which is supported by the ongoing media campaign Give Your Chance.
The most important person in the care of a patient with multiple sclerosis is a neurologist.
For multiple sclerosis, the adage is twice that the treatment of the disease is treated earlier, the more likely the doctor can make an impact.
This is because we have medication for multiple sclerosis at an inflammatory stage, when the neurodegeneration process is not so strong.
The earlier we intervene, the greater the hope that we will be able to stop the disease and delay the disability, explains MUDr. Eva Medová from the Neurological Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
It is very important in people with multiple sclerosis rehabilitation care, which most often solves the weakening of the lower limbs or balance disorders.
The patients are worked according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve walking, strengthening the pelvic floor, alleviating swallowing disorders or improving coordination.
"It's really individual, depending on the patient's specific problems," says M. Martina Kövári, head of the Clinic of Rehabilitation and Sports Medicine at the University Hospital Motol.
People with multiple sclerosis suffer from the same disease, but it manifests in a slightly different way for each.
Rehabilitation cannot stop the disease, but it can always alleviate its symptoms.
Motion activity, however, also strengthens the body's immune status, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another positive of regular exercise is the fact that the sick check for what they can do, and that reinforces their confidence.
"The exercise also flushes out endorphins and makes you feel good," the PhDr points out. Kamila Řasová from the Clinic of Rehabilitation Medicine at the Royal Vinohrady University Hospital.
By influencing the physical side, we act on the limbic system responsible for emotions.
We are directly interfering with the psyche and immune processes and stabilize the disease, he adds.
"Previously, these patients were so-called spared, now we know they need a targeted burden," says Prof. PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, head of the Clinic of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine of the University Hospital Motol.
Physiotherapy aims to allow a person to remain self-sufficient for as long as possible, including a job.
Physiotherapists are therefore working with ergoterpei to give each person a compensatory aid made to measure him.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or psychiatrist.
They're in a difficult life situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, it shakes people up.
They're in shock, panic, fear.
They must respond to the heavy burden - the loss of health.
With such a sore soul, we are to go to someone, not try to carry everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them so that they will eventually come to the conclusion that even with a handicap you can live a full life and that multiple sclerosis does not mean the end of life," says psychotherapist Renata Malinová - Schubertová from the Neurological Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
