‘Sonogenetics’ or control of brain cells using sound waves
This video shows how the sound impulses affect the direction the nematodes move.
Scientists have raised worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can be controlled by sound waves.
Tiny nematodes change direction when they are hit by sound impulses that are inaudible to the human ear.
Pulses work by switching off the cells of genetically modified motor neurons that are programmed to respond to these ultrasonic waves.
Related: Scientists can read and write brain activity using light
Scientists have reported that these worms are a great example of a new methodology called sonogenetics that uses ultrasound to activate the brain, heart, and muscle cells and activate outside the body.
Sekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that this method could one day replace deep brain stimulation - an invasive procedure in which electrodes that stimulate the brain of the patient are injected into the patient's brain. The method is used for example to treat the symptoms of Parkinson’s disease.
The mushroom usually doesn't respond to the ultrasound, but Chalasani found that the reaction would come when they were placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
The bubbles, he discovered, are amplified by ultrasound waves, which then pass through the worms' bodies.
The reinforced ultrasound waves are active in the TRP-4 ion channels, which are found in the membranes of some worm cells.
Thanks to the sound waves, these channels are opening and activating the cells they are linked to, a report from the journal Nature Communications.
In order to control the nematodes using ultrasound waves, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons contain the TRP-4 ion channels.
When he then used ultrasound for the worms so modified, the sound waves were amplified by microbububs and transferred to the worms, where they turned on the modified motor neurons.
The new method is similar in many ways to optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn on and off with the neurons using light.
Chalasani, however, has been quoted as saying that the sonogenetics could have many advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent by optical fibre to the desired place in the brain, ultrasonic waves can penetrate the tissues without any limit and be sent directly to the brain.
"We believe that if we use gene therapy and therapeutic viruses, we can target human neurons and make them temporarily sensitive to ultrasonic signals used in clinical treatment for neurological diseases," Chalasani said.
He added that the method would also find its application in the treatment of muscle cells and insulin-producing cells.
