Xi calls for the opening of the economy to the wider world
It is necessary to open up the economy to the wider world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told the group, whose task is Tuesday's governance reform.
"China should engage in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improving open policies," the central group's head of the Deepening the Over-Replant Reform said regarding the 16th meeting.
Promoting the opening up at the emerging reforms will give new impetus and vitality, and will also provide a new space for economic growth, says Xi.
The lead group adopted a number of directives, including a negative list of regulatory market access, the loosening of the border control policy, support for state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to absorb private capital and reorganisation of the SG&D system.
The statement states that a negative list will be drawn up to identify sectors and businesses that are outside the investment limits.
This system will be gradually tested and improved through test programmes.
This step is significant as it will give the market a greater role in the allocation of resources, ensure the business environment and make the market more open, the statement says.
The government will also release controls on the powers it delegates to firms and make sure that the firms themselves decide how to run their business.
The statement also states that China will allow the border areas to discover new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms for promoting regional growth.
In an effort to open up the state-controlled sector, more areas will be open to private investment.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legal interests of companies that are funded from abroad and will provide them with better services," the statement reads.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a "green card" by optimizing the requirements and simplifying the application process.
Provision of the rights of attorneys to practise and develop by professional judges and the prosecutor was also discussed at the meeting.
The meeting was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang and Lecturers Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
In the Karlovy Vary Region, new bed wards may be created.
According to the Deputy Governor of the Karlovy Vary Region, Jakub Pánik (ČSSD), the current capacity of the bed wards of two regional hospitals and two private hospitals in the region is sufficient and partial modifications should be made on the basis of an agreement between departments of individual hospitals.
In the region, however, there are also possibilities of expanding care.
For example, in the surgical department departments, there could be centers of one-day surgery, where surgical procedures would be performed according to the set concept, which do not require more than 24 hours of hospitalization.
In which specific hospitals the workplaces focused on one-day surgery should be, is not yet clear.
The skin department of the Karlovy Vary Hospital could in turn create a laser centre with the possibility of using laser technology for skin diseases.
The concept also recommended the creation of an apalic center to take care of patients with a natural brain disease who are in a vegetative state.
Such a centre should be established centrally and be an integral part of the anaesthetic-resuscitation department.
There is also the possibility of concentrating such a facility in the Ostrov hospital, where such care already exists.
Another bed capacity that appears to be insufficient in the Karlovy Vary Region is the aftercare bed and especially the bedbeds of the Long-Term Patients Treatment (LDN), whose capacity in Nejdek is insufficient and, above all, should closely connect to acute care beds.
Part of this facility should function as rehabilitation beds and part such as classic LDN beds, the concept recommends.
As he points out, the aftercare beds are mainly absent from the hospital in Karlovy Vary.
There, they could be used by the abandoned buildings after centralization.
Last but not least, in the Karlovy Vary Region, there are no social health beds with a focus on the treatment of Alzheimer's disease.
These beds are in short supply throughout the country, so it could also serve for other regions as the so-called Alzheimercentrum.
Hospitals should also prepare for the introduction of so-called follow-on beds, according to the recommendations, for which European subsidies will be mobilised.
"These are beds that will follow up on the subjects of supespecialised care and will form a space for the translation of patients after the procedure, for example, after the procedure, for example, after cardiac surgery, neurosurgical, transplantation or other procedure," the regional concept of inpatient care describes.
New services could also be offered in the area of psychiatric care.
